{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774293458,"nonce":"B/f+/DF7s3JFBaFyirgcdF/L1xQ=","title":"Worst-case training methods: APT and CVaR for minimax-like optimization","message":"## Summary\n\nBackprop minimizes expected cost (LQG family). To get H-infinity-like behavior (worst-case cost minimization), we need worst-case-oriented training. This does NOT require reinforcement learning — the differentiable simulator (JAX + Diffrax) supports nested gradient computation directly.\n\n## Two Methods\n\n### Adversarial Perturbation Training (APT)\n\nFor each training trial:\n1. Sample beta ~ U[0,1], set SISU = beta\n2. Initialize perturbation trajectory w = zeros\n3. Inner loop (3-5 gradient ascent steps):\n   - Forward pass: run full trial with current w\n   - Compute loss L\n   - w \u003c- w + alpha_adv * grad_w(L)  (ascend on w to maximize loss)\n   - Project w onto constraint: ||w||_2 \u003c= beta * sigma\n4. Outer step: with worst-case w fixed, backprop through full trial, update theta to minimize L\n\nThis is Madry et al. (2018) adversarial training applied to dynamical systems. It is literally the discrete-time nonlinear H-infinity game. Computationally ~3-5x more expensive per batch (extra forward passes for inner loop).\n\nKey property: the network is trained against worst-case perturbations within the energy budget set by SISU. This structurally prevents laziness and gain scheduling shortcuts because the adversary exploits them.\n\nNote: APT's inner loop is model-specific — the gradient ascent on w depends on the forward dynamics. If the model changes, the inner loop must be adjusted. This is relevant for Feedbax Studio integration (see dependency note below).\n\n### CVaR (Conditional Value-at-Risk)\n\nFor each SISU level, sample K perturbation realizations per trial, compute all K losses, sort, backprop only through the worst (1-alpha) fraction (e.g., worst 10%).\n\n- No inner loop, no adversary, no model-specific code\n- ~K x more compute per batch (K forward passes per trial)\n- Interpolates between expected-cost (alpha=0) and worst-case (alpha-\u003e1)\n- Could tie alpha to SISU: alpha(beta) = beta (higher uncertainty -\u003e more worst-case emphasis)\n- Implementable in ~10 lines of JAX\n\n## The Spectrum\n\nexpected cost -\u003e CVaR -\u003e APT -\u003e full H-infinity\n\nMove along it incrementally. CVaR is the cheapest experiment to test whether worst-case emphasis changes behavioral signatures (especially peak velocity).\n\n## Dependency: Feedbax Studio Training Method Control\n\nCurrently Studio uses baseline backprop. CVaR would be straightforward to add (just loss aggregation change). APT is harder — requires an inner optimization loop that is model-specific. This raises a design question about whether the training procedure should eventually be representable as a graph (related to the model graph). For now, an enum/selection might suffice, with APT requiring custom per-model inner-loop code. This should be filed as a separate issue in the Feedbax repo.\n\n## References\n\n- Madry et al. (2018) \"Towards Deep Learning Models Resistant to Adversarial Attacks\"\n- Long et al. (2024) \"Learning H-Infinity Locomotion Control\"\n- Rockafellar \u0026 Uryasev (2000) CVaR optimization\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}